Definition of For Loops
For loops let you repeat an action for each element of an object, usually a vector or list.
Syntax:
for (item in sequence of items) {
  action to be repeated for each item   
}
Example:
for (item in c(1,2,3)) {
  print(item)
}
What’s the repeated action here? How many times? What’s item?

Nested For Loops
In nested for loops the outer loop controls how many times the entire inner loop runs from start to end:

for (i in c(1,2,3)) {
  print(i)
  for (j in c("cat", "dog", "squirrel", "rabbit")) {
    print(j)
  }
}

What’s going on here?

The outer loop runs 3 times
For each execution of the outer loop, the inner loop runs 4 times

Loops + Conditional Statements
This is code from our last lecture:

numbers &lt;- c(10, 6, 7)
ifelse(numbers %% 2 == 1, 
       "odd",
       "even")

We can try to rewrite it using if-else statement, but we will get an error (recall why?):
numbers &lt;- c(10, 6, 7)
if (numbers %% 2 == 1) { 
  print("odd")
} else {
  print("even") }
But now we know how to fix that error: with a for loop! This way, the if-else runs one element at a time:

numbers &lt;- c(10, 6, 7)
for (i in 1:length(numbers)) {
  #print(i)
  #print(numbers[i])
  if (numbers[i] %% 2 == 1) {
    print("odd")
  } else {
    print("even")
  } }

While Loop Syntax
Syntax:
while (condition to be evaluated) {
  statement(s)
}
Example:
counter &lt;- 1

while(counter &lt;= 4) {
  print(counter)
  counter &lt;- counter + 1
}

While Loop Examples
Take the previous code, but this time we do not increment our counter variable. What is the output of this code?
counter &lt;- 1
while(counter &lt; 3){
  print(counter)
}

Writing custom functions
In R we can also write our own function!
For example, we could write our own sum function to calculate the sum of the elements of a numeric vector, like this:
my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)
my_sum(x)
Let’s unpack this code…

Writing custom functions
Tip! Write and test the code outside a function to make sure it works, like this:

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)

total &lt;- 0
for (i in seq_along(x)) {
  total &lt;- total + x[i]
}
total

Then wrap the code into a function and test it with different inputs:

my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)
my_sum(vector = x)

y &lt;- c(4,4)
my_sum(y)

Tips for writing functions: variables scope
Variables defined inside a function are not available outside it. Their scope lies within and is limited to the function itself.
Run this in a fresh R session: total exists only inside my_sum():
my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)
my_sum(x)
total   # Error: object 'total' not found

The return statement(s)
If you do not write a return statement, your output will be the last statement in your code:

my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  total
}

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)
my_sum(x)

This works, but it’s best practice to use return for clarity and readability. Remember that any code after return will be ignored! Let’s see a couple of examples…

Write multiple return statements: Example 1

describe_number &lt;- function(x) {
  if (x == 0) {
    return("x is zero (special case!)")
  }
  if (x &gt; 0) {
    return("x is positive")
  } else {
    return("x is negative")
  }
}

Write multiple return statements: Example 2

my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {

  # check 1: input must not be missing
  if (missing(vector)) {
    return("Error: you must provide a vector")
  }

  # check 2: input must be numeric
  if (!is.numeric(vector)) {
    return("Error: input must be a numeric vector")
  }

  # compute the sum
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

# examples
my_sum(c(2, 1, 5, 2))
my_sum(c("one", 2, 3))
my_sum()

Questions: Why we do not write the “else” in this example? Can you do the same with the previous one?

Write one return statement with multiple outputs
Sometimes you want to return multiple objects and collect them into a list or a vector:
my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(list(total, i))
}

x &lt;- c(2,1,5,2)
y &lt;- my_sum(x)
Questions: Can we return a vector rather than list here? How? A list is generally be a better choice when your function returns multiple objects. Why?

Using stop() when writing a function
Define a function celsius_to_fahr() that converts temperatures from Celsius to Fahrenheit using the formula fahrenheit = (celsius * 9/5) + 32
celsius_to_fahr &lt;- function(celsius) {
  fahr &lt;- (celsius * 9/5) + 32
  return(fahr)
}

celsius_to_fahr(0)
celsius_to_fahr(-20)

Using stop() when writing a function
To ensure this function works properly, the argument must be numeric. Otherwise, the conversion between the two temperature scales will not work.
Thus, we use if-else to verify if the provided argument is numeric. If not, we use stop() to raise an error and stop the function execution!
celsius_to_fahr &lt;- function(celsius) {
  if (!is.numeric(celsius)) {
    stop("error: input must be a number, try again")
  } else {
    fahr &lt;- (celsius * 9/5) + 32
    return(fahr) 
  }
}

celsius_to_fahr("zero")
Question: Based on what you see in this code, what’s the difference between stop() and return()?

Using stop() when writing a function: obseve this comparison
Approach 1: using return() for errors ❌
my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {

  # input check with return(): the error message is just a regular value
  if (!is.numeric(vector)) {
    return("Error: input must be a numeric vector")
  }

  # compute the sum
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

result &lt;- my_sum(c("one", 2, 3))  # no error shown!
result                            # only now we see something is off
result + 10                       # fails HERE, with a confusing message

Using stop() when writing a function: obseve this comparison
Approach 2: using stop() for errors ✅
my_sum &lt;- function(vector) {

  # input check with stop(): raise a real error
  if (!is.numeric(vector)) {
    stop("input must be a numeric vector")
  }

  # compute the sum (identical to previous code)
  total &lt;- 0
  for (i in seq_along(vector)) {
    total &lt;- total + vector[i]
  }
  return(total)
}

result &lt;- my_sum(c("one", 2, 3))  # Error: input must be a numeric vector, halts immediately
                                  # with OUR message; result is never created
result + 10                       # in a script, this line is never reached

Example from Google’s R Style Guide here

CalculateSampleCovariance &lt;- function(x, y, verbose = TRUE) {

  # Computes the sample covariance between two vectors.
  # Args:
  #   x: One of two vectors whose sample covariance is to be calculated.
  #   y: The other vector. x and y must have the same length, greater than one,
  #      with no missing values.
  #   verbose: If TRUE, prints sample covariance; if not, not. Default is TRUE.
  # Returns:
  #   The sample covariance between x and y.

  n &lt;- length(x)
  if (n &lt;= 1 || n != length(y)) {
    stop("Arguments x and y have invalid lengths: ",
         length(x), " and ", length(y), ".") }
  if (TRUE %in% is.na(x) || TRUE %in% is.na(y)) {
    stop(" Arguments x and y must not have missing values.") }
  covariance &lt;- var(x, y)
  if (verbose)
    cat("Covariance = ", round(covariance, 4), ".\n", sep = "")
  return(covariance)
}

Functions and {{ }}
Rewrite the previous code using a function and the curly-curly operator (embracing):

custom_summary &lt;- function(data, col) {
  data %&gt;%
    summarize(mean_value = mean({{ col }}),
              sd_value = sd({{ col }}))
}

custom_summary(df, age)

# A tibble: 1 × 2
  mean_value sd_value
       &lt;dbl&gt;    &lt;dbl&gt;
1       11.8     1.79


The { } operator tells dplyr not to treat “col” as the literal variable name, but instead to look inside it for the variable we actually need (here “age”)

